<Base title="Home" description="Charlotte Joanne Tyrer — founder of Blind Ant, the CharliVerse, and the Museum of Access and Assistive Technology." type="WebSite">
  <h1>We have equality.</h1>

  <p>Blind people have the same relationship with technology as everyone else in 2026.</p>

  <p>I've been thinking about the first three months of this year. I use AI a lot - maybe not 996, but after two mugs of coffee and feeding my dragons, I open my laptop and that tends to be me for the next twelve hours.</p>

  <p>There have been a number of articles and podcasts lately talking about AI burnout, AI brain rot, and the latest: AI brain fry. This latest can be described as people having so much to do that they want to do even more. I think it's completely made up. I myself have nothing more than:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>A part-time degree in Philosophy and Psychology to complete.</li>
    <li>A three-to-six month plan to develop and launch Red DOG Studio - an autonomous NVDA add-on creation process.</li>
    <li>A ten-year plan to found a Museum of Access and Assistive Technology.</li>
    <li>A LinkedIn newsletter.</li>
    <li>A Substack newsletter.</li>
    <li>Blind Ant, a CharliVerse Lived Experience Validation studio.</li>
    <li>And last, but not least, an online community of more than a thousand blind AI enthusiasts to help shepherd.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>The truth is that this isn't overload - it's the reality of working with AI in 2026. When the tools actually work, one person can operate across spaces that previously required teams, departments, and budgets. Writing, analysis, design, community building, prototyping - the barriers between them have largely disappeared. What used to be separate roles now collapse into a single flow of curiosity and execution.</p>

  <p>For me, the real change is something simpler. For most of my life, doing anything with technology meant paying what I call the tinker tax - the hidden labour of making tools work at all. Fighting inaccessible interfaces, stitching together workflows, persuading software to behave long before you could actually start the real task. AI changes that equation. When the tools finally meet you halfway, the energy that used to be spent wrestling the machinery is suddenly available for thinking.</p>

  <p>And when that happens, something unexpected appears. What looks like "a lot of work" from the outside doesn't feel like work from the inside. It feels like play. Ideas lead to experiments, experiments lead to posts, posts lead to conversations, conversations lead to new projects. It's not a workload so much as a landscape you get to wander through. For the first time in a long time, the technology isn't the obstacle. It's the thing that lets the mind run free.</p>

